The analysis process includes determining the a.m. and p.m. peak-hour operations at the study
intersections, freeway segments, and operations daily along the roadway segments. Intersections were
measured and quantified using the Synchro traffic analysis software package. Results will be compared to
the City’s thresholds to determine if the project has any significant traffic impacts.
To analyze the operations of both signalized and unsignalized intersections, Synchro 8.0 (Trafficware) was
used for the analysis. Synchro 8.0 uses the methodologies outlined in the 2000 Highway Capacity Manual
(HCM). The existing intersection peak-hour factor (PHF) was used for Existing and Near Term scenarios.
A PHF of 0.92 was used for Horizon Year conditions to account for the unknown change in traffic patterns.

The 2010 Highway Capacity Manual (HCM) published by the Transportation Research Board establishes
a system whereby highway facilities are rated for their ability to process traffic volumes. The terminology
"level of service" is used to provide a "qualitative" evaluation based on certain "quantitative" calculations,
which are related to empirical values.
Level of service (LOS) for signalized intersections is defined in terms of delay, which is a measure of driver
discomfort, frustration, fuel consumption, and loss of travel time. Specifically, LOS criteria are stated in
terms of the average control delay per vehicle for the peak 15-minute period within the hour analyzed. The
average control delay includes initial deceleration delay, queue move-up time, and final acceleration time
in additional to the stop delay. The level of service for unsignalized intersections is determined by the
computed or measured control delay and is defined for each minor movement. The criteria for the various
levels of service designations for signalized and unsignalized intersections are given in Table 2-2.
Within the City of San Diego, all signalized and unsignalized intersections are considered deficient if they
operate at LOS E or F.

The City of San Diego and Caltrans have developed acceptable threshold standards to determine the
significance of project impacts to intersections, roadway segments, freeway segments, and freeway ramp
metering. At intersections, the measurement of effectiveness (MOE) is based on allowable increases in
delay. Along roadway segments and freeway segments, the MOE is based on allowable increases in the
volume-to-capacity (v/c) ratio. At a freeway ramp meter, the MOE is based on allowable increases in delay,
LOS F is not acceptable for any approach leg except for side streets on an interconnected arterial system.
If vehicle trips from a project cause an intersection approach leg to operate at LOS F, except in the cases
of side streets on an interconnected arterial system, this would be considered a significant project traffic
impact that requires mitigation. At intersections that are expected to operate at LOS E or F without the
project, the allowable increase in delay is two seconds at LOS E and one second at LOS F with the addition
of the project. If vehicle trips from a project cause the delay at an intersection to increase by more than the
allowable threshold, this would be considered a significant project impact that requires mitigation. Also, if
the project causes an intersection that was operating at an acceptable LOS to operate at LOS E or F, this
would be considered a significant project impact that requires mitigation.
For roadway segments that are forecasted to operate at LOS E or F with the project, the allowable increase
in v/c ratio is 0.02 at LOS E and 0.01 at LOS F. If vehicle trips from a project cause the v/c ratio to increase
by more than the allowable threshold, this would be considered a significant project traffic impact that
requires mitigation. Also, if the project causes a street segment that was operating at an acceptable LOS
to operate at LOS E or F, this would be considered a significant impact that requires mitigation.
Where the roadway segment operates at LOS E or F, if the intersections at the ends of the segment are
calculated to operate at an acceptable LOS with the project; and a peak hour HCM arterial analysis for the
same segment shows that the segment operates at an acceptable LOS with the project; then the project
impacts are determined to be less than significant and no mitigation is required. If analysis shows either the
intersections or segment under the peak hour HCM analysis do not operate acceptably, the project impacts
are considered significant and unmitigated, requiring the adoption of findings of infeasibility and a statement
of over-riding considerations before the project may be approved.
In certain instances mitigation may not be required even if a roadway segment operates at LOS E or LOS
F. In such cases the following three conditions must all be met:
The roadway is built to its ultimate classification per the community plan;
The intersections on both ends of the failing segment operate at an acceptable LOS; and
An HCM arterial analysis indicates an acceptable LOS on the segment.
For freeway segments that are forecasted to operate at LOS E or F with the project, the allowable increase
in v/c ratio is 0.01 at LOS E and 0.005 at LOS F. If vehicle trips from a project cause the v/c ratio to increase
by more than the allowable threshold, this would be considered a significant project traffic impact that
requires mitigation. Also, if the project causes a freeway segment that was operating at an acceptable LOS
to operate at LOS E or F, this would be considered a significant impact that requires mitigation.

Beyer Boulevard is classified as a Four-Lane Major street that has an east-west alignment from Dairy Mart
Road to East Beyer Boulevard. This major street runs parallel to the railroad tracks then turns north into
the Otay Mesa-Nestor community. Gutters, curbs, and sidewalks are present along this corridor. Parallel
parking is provided along the south side of the roadway between Dairy Mart Road and Smythe Crossing,
and along both sides of the roadway between Smythe Crossing and East Beyer Boulevard. The posted
speed limit along Beyer Boulevard is 40 mph between Dairy Mart Road and Del Sur Boulevard and 35 mph
between Del Sur Boulevard and East Beyer Boulevard. Beyer Boulevard is surrounded by the railroad
tracks along the south side and by commercial and residential uses along the north side. Beyer Boulevard
is classified as a Class III bicycle facility. The City BMP proposes Beyer Boulevard as a Class II (bike lane)
facility between Dairy Mart Road and Smythe Avenue.
East Beyer Boulevard is classified as a Two-Lane Collector that has a north-south alignment from Beyer
Boulevard to East San Ysidro Boulevard. This street is located east of Interstate 805 and Interstate 5 and
runs parallel to both of these facilities. Parallel parking is available on both sides of the street. The east
side of the street has a curb and gutter. The posted speed limit along East Beyer Boulevard is 30 mph
between Beyer Boulevard and Bolton Hall Road and 40 mph between Bolton Hall and East San Ysidro
Boulevard. East Beyer Boulevard is classified as a Class III bicycle facility. The City BMP proposes East
Beyer Boulevard as a Class II (bike lane) facility.
Del Sur Boulevard is classified as a Two-Lane Collector with two-way left-turn lanes that has a north-south
alignment from the Otay Mesa Nestor community to Beyer Boulevard. Parallel parking is available on the
east side of the street. Diagonal parking is available between Shooting Start Drive and Caithness Drive.
Curb, gutter and sidewalks are present along both sides of the street. Del Sur Boulevard provides access
for the industrial area located between State Route 905 and Beyer Boulevard and for residential uses north
of Beyer Boulevard. The posted speed limit along Del Sur Boulevard is 30 mph. Del Sur Boulevard is
classified as a Class II Bicycle Facility. The City BMP does not propose any improvements to the bicycle
Smythe Avenue is classified as a Four-Lane Collector between State Route 905 and Beyer Boulevard and
as a Two-Lane Collector between Beyer Boulevard and West San Ysidro Boulevard. Curb, gutter and
sidewalks are present along both sides of the street. Parking is not provided between State Route 905 and
Beyer Boulevard. Between Beyer Boulevard and West San Ysidro Boulevard, Smythe Avenue provides
service to residential uses and parallel parking is provide along both sides of the roadway. The posted
speed limit between State Route 905 and Beyer Boulevard is 35 mph. Between Beyer Boulevard and West
San Ysidro Boulevard it is 25 mph. Smythe Avenue is classified as a Class II bicycle facility between State
Route 905 and Beyer Boulevard. The City BMP does not propose any improvements to the bicycle facilities
Dairy Mart Road is classified as a Four-Lane Collector that runs in the north-south direction from Beyer
Boulevard to Camino de la Plaza. South of Camino de la Plaza, Dairy Mart Road is classified as a two-lane
collector. The segment between the West San Ysidro Boulevard and Camino de la Plaza is not yet built to
its ultimate classification and functions as a Two-Lane Collector roadway. This road provides access to the
Tijuana River Valley. There are curbs, gutters, and sidewalks along both sides of the roadway between
Beyer Boulevard and West San Ysidro Boulevard. Parking is not provided along the entire roadway
segment. The posted speed limit along Dairy Mart Road is 30 mph between Beyer Boulevard and the
Interstate 5 interchange. Between the Interstate 5 interchange and Camino de la Plaza, the posted speed
limit is 40 mph. Between Beyer Boulevard and Vista Lane, Dairy Mart Road is surrounded by single-family
residential uses. Between Vista Lane and the West San Ysidro Boulevard, the uses along the west side of
Dairy Mart Road are commercial while the east side has multi-family residential uses. South of Intertate 5,
Dairy Mart Road is bordered by the Tijuana River Valley open space. Dairy Mart Road is part of the existing
bicycle network and functions as a Class II bicycle facility between Beyer Boulevard and West San Ysidro
Boulevard. The City BMP proposes Dairy Mart Road south of San Ysidro Boulevard as a Class II (bike lane)
San Ysidro Boulevard is the primary thoroughfare in the San Ysidro community. West San Ysidro
Boulevard is classified as a Two-Lane Collector from Howard Avenue to Dairy Mart Road, as a three-lane
collector from Dairy Mart Road to Sunset Lane, and back to a Two-Lane Collector classification from Sunset
Lane to Via de San Ysidro. West San Ysidro Boulevard widens to a Four-Lane Major arterial from Via San
Ysidro to the Interstate 805 ramps. East San Ysidro Boulevard is classified as a Two-Lane Collector from the
Interstate 805 ramps to Border Village Road (east), then widens to a Four-Lane Major arterial from Border
Village Road (east) to East Beyer Boulevard-Camino de la Plaza. There is a continuous left turn lane from
Sunset Lane to Cottonwood Road and also from the Interstate 805 ramps to Border Village Road (east). Curbs,
gutters, sidewalks, and parking exist. The posted speed limit along San Ysidro Boulevard is 35 mph with the
exception of the segments between Averil Road and Cottonwood Road where the posted speed limit is 25
mph. San Ysidro Boulevard is surrounded by multi-family, commercial and industrial uses. The City BMP
proposes San Ysidro Boulevard as a Class II (bike lane) facility.

Boulevard at two locations. Under existing conditions, Border Village Road functions as a Two-Lane Collector.
This roadway is built to support the commercial/industrial uses south of East San Ysidro Boulevard. Curb,
gutter and sidewalks are provided along both sides of the roadway. Parking is also provided along both sides.
The speed limit along Border Village Road is 30 mph. The City BMP proposes Border Village Road as a Class
Via de San Ysidro is classified as a Four-Lane Major roadway connecting West San Ysidro Boulevard with

Camino de la Plaza is classified as a Four-Lane Collector that runs in the east-west direction. There are

Interstate 5 is a significant north-south interstate that traverses the United States from the Mexico border
to the Canadian border through the states of California, Oregon, and Washington. Within California, I-5
connects the following major metropolitan areas: San Diego, Los Angeles, Sacramento, and the eastern
portion of the San Francisco Bay Area. I-5 can be directly accessed from the San Ysidro community and
provides access to I-805 and SR-905 within the vicinity of the study area. Within the San Ysidro study area,

Interstate 805 is a north – south interstate within the San Diego County limits. I-805 provides connections with
I-5, SR-163, and SR-905 within the vicinity of the study area. Within the San Ysidro study area, I-805 has one
local interchange at San Ysidro Boulevard and provides southbound travel an exit opportunity at Camino
State Route 905 serves as a major east-west connection between the Interstate 5 and the Otay Mesa
community. State Route 905 has two local interchanges at Beyer Boulevard and Picador Boulevard.
The peak-hour intersection turning movements at all study area intersections and the average daily traffic
(ADT) volumes were obtained from several sources. Where appropriate, traffic counts from previous
studies were utilized since traffic volumes within certain areas of the community generally remained
constant. For the counts listed in the Year 2007, traffic data was obtained from the San Ysidro Mobility
Strategy, prepared by Kimley-Horn and Associates. For the counts listed in the Year 2008, traffic data was
obtained from the San Ysidro Land Port of Entry Expansion Mobility Study, prepared by KOA Corporation.
For the counts listed in the Year 2010, traffic data was obtained by National Data and Surveying Services
and True Counts. All weekday counts were collected on a Tuesday, Wednesday or Thursday.
In accordance with the City of San Diego Traffic Impact Study Manual (1998), traffic counts should be no
greater than two years old. Therefore, since the counts were gathered between 2007 and 2010, validation
was required to determine if the counts still represent current traffic conditions for this report. Consequently,
the roadway segment ADT counts were compared to the current (i.e., Year 2010 through 2012) City of San
Diego machine counts available for the San Ysidro community and adjacent freeway ramp facilities to
determine if the counts included were still valid. The existing traffic volume data and current City of San
Diego machine counts are contained in Appendix C.
Although it does appear that traffic volumes have increased in the community since 2007 through 2010,
when the existing counts were collected, new counts are not necessary. The project’s impacts are based
upon the change between the existing condition and the horizon year condition. The impacts identified in
this study are therefore conservative. The time delay and expense of conducting new counts is not justified

The Dairy Mart Road and Camino de la Plaza intersection is a one-way stop controlled intersection. The

The Camino de la Plaza and Interstate 5 southbound ramps experience significant delay due to the

At the intersection of Vista Lane & Smythe Crossing, the eastbound movement experiences the largest

In the process of calibrating the existing model, it was concluded that several post model adjustments were

page.text: Year 2035 peak hour turning movements at the study area intersections were developed using
methodologies from National Cooperative Highway Research Program (NCHRP) 255 – Highway Traffic
Data for Urbanized Area Project Planning and Design, Chapter 8. NCHRP Report 255 is a compilation of
the best techniques that are currently being used in urban areas to forecast future traffic volumes. These
techniques were identified through a survey of state and local agencies with follow-up field visits to obtain
detailed information on procedural steps and typical applications. The method used to forecast the future
turning movement volumes for the San Ysidro Community Plan evaluation is the NCHRP’s “Directional
Volume Forecast”. For this method, existing and future daily traffic volumes, existing peak hour turning
movements, and projected peak hour “K” and directional “D” factors are applied to future forecasted ADT
volumes and used to calculate future year turning movements. Existing daily segment traffic volumes and
peak hour intersection turning movements were counted in the field. Year 2035 daily traffic volumes were
obtained from the forecast model forecast. Using the “Directional Volume Forecast” technique, the existing
turning movements at each study area intersection were factored based on increases in daily approach
traffic and existing K and D factors. Each respective movement was derived using an iterative approach
that balances the inflows and outflows for each approach. The supporting worksheets for calculating Year
2035 volumes are included in Appendix F. Resulting peak hour intersection turning movements are
